  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div xml:id="KT193-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">tōḻi kaṭinakar pukku “nalan tolaiyāmē naṉku āṟṟiṉāy” eṉṟāṭkuk kiḻatti uraittatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Told by HER to her who said “we have not lost [our] beauty. you have well had the strength”, after the confidante had entered the marriage house.</p>
          </div>
          

        <div xml:id="KT193">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                maṭṭam peyta maṇikkalat taṉṉa</l>
<l>                viṭṭuvāyc cuṉaiya pakuvāyt tērai</l>
<l>                taṭṭaip paṟaiyiṟ kaṟaṅku nāṭaṉ</l>
<l>                ṟollait tiṅka ṇeṭuveṇ ṇilaviṉ</l>
<l>                maṇantaṉaṉ maṉṉeṭun tōḷē</l>
<l>                yiṉṟu mullai mukainā ṟummē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
     <l rend="indent">In the long white light of the old moon</l>
     <l>the man from a land, where the wide-mouthed frog sounds</l>
     <l rend="indent">like the bird-chasing drum, in the narrow-mouthed mountain pool</l>
     <l rend="indent">like a sapphire pot filled with toddy,<note place="foot">For <term xml:lang="ta">maṭṭam peyta maṇi kalattu</term> TVG considers the alternative interpretation of <term xml:lang="ta">maṭṭam</term> as Greek wine, brought in <term xml:lang="ta">nal kalam</term>, in "good vessels", as mentioned in PN 56.16-21, though there is no hint as to the colour of these <term xml:lang="ta">kalam</term>-s.</note></l>
     <l>indeed united<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">maṇantaṉaṉ</term>: here it is uncertain whether the perfective aspect is used to denote past tense. It might also mean that the union is already on the way.</note> with [her of] long shoulders.</l>
     <l>Today the jasmine buds are fragrant.</l>
     <lg type="alternate" resp="#TVG" sameAs="4-6b">
      <l>In the previous month, in the long white moonlight</l>
      <l>he united [with me] of long shoulders.</l>
      <l>Even today<note place="foot">The <term xml:lang="ta">sandhi</term> also allows for the reading <term xml:lang="ta">iṉṟum</term> "even today, still today".</note> they (my shoulders) are fragrant with jasmine buds.<note place="foot">Thus the scholastic interpretation in accordance with the <term xml:lang="ta">kiḷavi</term>: SHE reassures her confidante that she will patiently await his coming for the marriage, because sweet memories keep her upright.</note></l>
     </lg>

            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
